aa(lp169
VHaving gone through the data, I then needed
p170
aVto demonstrate where that food ends up.
p171
aVWhere does it end up? We're used to seeing the stuff
p172
aVon our plates, but what about all the stuff
p173
aVthat goes missing in between?
p174
aa(lp175
VSupermarkets are an easy place to start.
p176
aVThis is the result of my hobby,
p177
aVwhich is unofficial bin inspections. (Laughter)
p178
aVStrange you might think, but if we could rely on corporations
p179
aVto tell us what they were doing in the back of their stores,
p180
aVwe wouldn't need to go sneaking around the back,
p181
aVopening up bins and having a look at what's inside.
p182
aVBut this is what you can see more or less on
p183
aVevery street corner in Britain, in Europe, in North America.
p184
aVIt represents a colossal waste of food,
p185
aVbut what I discovered whilst I was writing my book
p186
aVwas that this very evident abundance of waste
p187
aVwas actually the tip of the iceberg.
p188
aVWhen you start going up the supply chain,
p189
aVyou find where the real food waste is happening
p190
aVon a gargantuan scale.
p191
aa(lp192
